The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Bharti forges cable Unity
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Bharti forges cable Unity
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, April 1: A global consortium having Indias No. 1 mobile phone company Bharti Airtel as a member today launched an undersea cable system, called Unity, that links Japan to the western coast of US.        
	Bharti is building bandwidth capacity through numerous undersea cable systems, of which it is a sole owner of one  i2i  with the rest it owns as part of a consortium. The Unity cable system links Chikura in Japan with three points in the US  Los Angeles, Palo Alto and San Jose.         
	Bhartis i2i cable links India with Singapore; as part of global consortiums it has ownerships of the South East Asia-Middle East-Western European 4 (SEA-ME-WE), Europe India Gateway (EIG), India-Middle East-Western Europe (I-ME-WE) and Asia-America Gateway (AAG) cable systems.        
	The Unity cable system will provide enhanced and seamless global connectivity, as it is connected to other cable systems further enhancing connectivity to Asia, said Rajan Swaroop, executive director (enterprise services), Bharti Airtel.        
	Construction of the cable system was first announced in February 2008 by the Unity consortium, which comprises Bharti, Global Transit, Google, KDDI Corporation, Pacnet and SingTel.         
	The system was built at a cost of around $300 million. It is designed to deliver up to 4.8 terabits per second of bandwidth across the Pacific, with each fibre pair having a capacity of up to 960 gigabits per second.                                                                                                                                       
